People shit talk the dragonborn for being too humanoid but they were so well done. I don't know of any other "realistic" depiction of an anthro that has the same level of attention to facial expressions and body language that they got in this game.

Most of the attention during dialogue is on faces in this game yet obviously irl animals (specially lizards) do not communicate and display emotion with their faces. So the devs had to get very creative in coming up with ways for their faces to emote enough on the same level as a human face through lip movements, facial muscles, the way their eyelids move and lots of exagerrated snappy body movements during their dialogue.
Having different parts of their head face the camera to emphasize different facial expressions since they looked like they were making different emotes depending on if you were looking at them from above, below, the side, etc.
https://youtu.be/W-GW3-0rJvw
It's something that isn't explored very often because 2D anthros "cheat" with certain facial expressions (think of anthro snouts turning into tubes with lips for kisses) and 3D anthros likewise use stylized and cartoony tricks to avoid dealing with the rather stiff emotional range a snout provides
